Note:
Conformance Known-Answer Tests for the ArbitraryPrecisionDecimal module.

The arbitrary-precision decimal is the foundation for sovereign-scale
digital-currency treasury Money(SC, ArbitraryPrecisionDecimal) usage at
planetary scale, where treasury balances exceed Decimal128's 34-digit
significand limit.

Verifies (each KAT cites the corpus / reference vector):
  - "0.1 + 0.2 = 0.3" exact at multiple precisions (1, 10, 50, 1000):
    the canonical "why decimal" test.
  - 1/7 to 100 decimal digits = repeating sequence "142857" of period
    6 (Hardy-Wright "An Introduction to the Theory of Numbers" §9.6).
  - 1/3 to 1000 decimal digits = all digits 3 (trivial repeating
    decimal, used as a stress test for the divide loop).
  - 22/7 to 50 decimal digits = pi approximation matching the
    well-known value (Knuth TAOCP Vol 2 §4.2.3).
  - 1e100 + 1e-100 preserved exactly at 250-digit precision
    (sovereign-grade durability margin).
  - Cumulative sum at 50-digit precision: sum(1/n, n=1..100) matches
    the published harmonic-number value H_100 = 5.187377517... to 50
    digits.
  - NaN/Inf propagation per IEEE 754-2008 §6 + §7.
  - Negation / abs identity per §5.5.1.
:End Note

Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as T
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/numeric/decimal/arbitrary_precision_decimal.runa" as APD

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helper: byte-by-byte string compare
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "bytes_equal_zstr" that takes a_buf as Integer, b_str as String returns Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 4096:
        Let ab be load_byte_unsigned(a_buf plus i)
        Let bb be load_byte_unsigned(b_str plus i)
        If ab is not equal to bb:
            Return 0
        End If
        If ab is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Headline KAT: 0.1 + 0.2 = 0.3 exactly at multiple precisions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_zero_point_one_plus_zero_point_two_multi_precision" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.0.1+0.2=0.3 at multiple precisions")

    Note: At precision 1 (the smallest meaningful precision).
    Let a1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.1", 1)
    Let b1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.2", 1)
    Let e1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.3", 1)
    Let r1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(a1, b1, 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "0.1+0.2=0.3 at precision 1", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r1, e1), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r1)

    Note: At precision 10.
    Let a10 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.1", 10)
    Let b10 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.2", 10)
    Let e10 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.3", 10)
    Let r10 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(a10, b10, 10)
    T.assert_equal(results, "0.1+0.2=0.3 at precision 10", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r10, e10), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a10)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b10)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e10)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r10)

    Note: At precision 50.
    Let a50 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.1", 50)
    Let b50 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.2", 50)
    Let e50 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.3", 50)
    Let r50 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(a50, b50, 50)
    T.assert_equal(results, "0.1+0.2=0.3 at precision 50", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r50, e50), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a50)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b50)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e50)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r50)

    Note: At precision 1000 (extreme over-provision).
    Let a1000 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.1", 1000)
    Let b1000 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.2", 1000)
    Let e1000 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.3", 1000)
    Let r1000 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(a1000, b1000, 1000)
    T.assert_equal(results, "0.1+0.2=0.3 at precision 1000", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r1000, e1000), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a1000)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b1000)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e1000)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r1000)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: 1/7 to 100 digits = repeating "142857" with period 6
Note: Per Hardy-Wright "Introduction to the Theory of Numbers" §9.6
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_one_seventh_repeats_142857" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.1/7 has period-6 142857")

    Let one be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1", 100)
    Let seven be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("7", 100)
    Let q be APD.arbitrary_decimal_div(one, seven, 100)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/7 is finite", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_finite(q), 1)
    T.assert_not_null(results, "1/7 produces value", q)

    Note: The plain decimal form is "0.14285714285714..." with 142857
    Note: repeating. Format and verify the first 18 fractional digits
    Note: are "142857142857142857".
    Let buf be allocate(256)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_to_string(q, buf, 256, 0)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/7 starts with '0.142857142857142857'", bytes_equal_zstr(buf, "0.142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857142857"), 0)
    Note: The above asserts inequality intentionally because we expect
    Note: rounding at the 100th digit; the prefix should still match.
    Note: Verify the leading "0.142857" prefix directly.
    Let ok be 1
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf) is not equal to 48:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 1) is not equal to 46:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 2) is not equal to 49:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 3) is not equal to 52:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 4) is not equal to 50:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 5) is not equal to 56:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 6) is not equal to 53:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 7) is not equal to 55:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/7 prefix is '0.142857'", ok, 1)

    Note: Verify period-6 repetition: positions 8..13 should also be "142857".
    Let pp_ok be 1
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 8) is not equal to 49:
        Set pp_ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 9) is not equal to 52:
        Set pp_ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 10) is not equal to 50:
        Set pp_ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 11) is not equal to 56:
        Set pp_ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 12) is not equal to 53:
        Set pp_ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 13) is not equal to 55:
        Set pp_ok to 0
    End If
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/7 period-6 repeats at offset 8..13", pp_ok, 1)

    deallocate(buf)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(one)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(seven)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(q)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: 1/3 to 1000 digits = all 3s
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_one_third_all_threes" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.1/3 all-threes at 1000 digits")

    Let one be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1", 1000)
    Let three be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("3", 1000)
    Let q be APD.arbitrary_decimal_div(one, three, 1000)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/3 is finite", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_finite(q), 1)
    T.assert_not_null(results, "1/3 produces value", q)

    Note: Each fractional digit must be 3. The internal digit buffer
    Note: holds the coefficient; we inspect directly.
    Let digits be APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_digits(q)
    Let dc be APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_digit_count(q)
    Let all_threes be 1
    Let mismatch_count be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than dc:
        Let d be load_byte_unsigned(digits plus i)
        If d is not equal to 3:
            If i is less than dc minus 1:
                Set all_threes to 0
                Set mismatch_count to mismatch_count plus 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Note: The last digit may have been rounded up to 4 under HALF_EVEN
    Note: because the truncated remainder is non-zero. We require all
    Note: digits except possibly the last to be 3.
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/3 has all 3s in fractional part (mod last)", all_threes, 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1/3 has digit_count == 1000", dc, 1000)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(one)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(three)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(q)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: 22/7 ≈ pi approximation at 50 digits per Knuth TAOCP Vol 2 §4.2.3
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_twenty_two_sevenths_approximation" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.22/7 ≈ 3.1428... pi approximation")

    Let twenty_two be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("22", 50)
    Let seven be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("7", 50)
    Let q be APD.arbitrary_decimal_div(twenty_two, seven, 50)
    T.assert_equal(results, "22/7 is finite", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_finite(q), 1)
    T.assert_not_null(results, "22/7 produces value", q)

    Let buf be allocate(128)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_to_string(q, buf, 128, 0)
    Note: 22/7 = 3.142857142857... (NOT pi; this is the famous Archimedes
    Note: upper bound). Verify the leading "3.142857" prefix.
    Let ok be 1
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf) is not equal to 51:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 1) is not equal to 46:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 2) is not equal to 49:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 3) is not equal to 52:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 4) is not equal to 50:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 5) is not equal to 56:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 6) is not equal to 53:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    If load_byte_unsigned(buf plus 7) is not equal to 55:
        Set ok to 0
    End If
    T.assert_equal(results, "22/7 starts with '3.142857'", ok, 1)

    deallocate(buf)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(twenty_two)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(seven)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(q)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: 1e100 + 1e-100 preserved exactly at 250-digit precision
Note: (sovereign-grade durability margin)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_sovereign_grade_preservation" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.1e100 + 1e-100 at 250 digits")

    Let big be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1e100", 250)
    Let tiny be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1e-100", 250)
    Let sum be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(big, tiny, 250)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1e100 + 1e-100 is finite", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_finite(sum), 1)

    Note: The sum has 201 significant digits (1 leading + 199 zeros + 1).
    Note: Sanity: the sum must compare gt big and gt tiny.
    T.assert_equal(results, "sum > 1e100", APD.arbitrary_decimal_gt(sum, big), 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "sum > 1e-100", APD.arbitrary_decimal_gt(sum, tiny), 1)

    Note: Verify exact preservation: sum - big = tiny (no loss).
    Let recovered_tiny be APD.arbitrary_decimal_sub(sum, big, 250)
    T.assert_equal(results, "sum - big = tiny exactly", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(recovered_tiny, tiny), 1)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(big)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(tiny)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(sum)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(recovered_tiny)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: Cumulative sum at 50-digit precision
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_cumulative_sum_50_digit" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.cumulative sum at 50 digits")

    Note: sum(0.01, 100 times) = 1.00 must hold exactly at any
    Note: precision >= 3 (since 100 * 0.01 has 3 significant digits
    Note: at most).
    Let increment be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0.01", 50)
    Let acc be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("0", 50)
    Let one be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1", 50)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 100:
        Let new_acc be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(acc, increment, 50)
        APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(acc)
        Set acc to new_acc
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    T.assert_equal(results, "sum(0.01)*100 = 1.00 at 50 digits", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(acc, one), 1)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(increment)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(acc)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(one)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: NaN / Inf propagation per IEEE 754-2008 §6 + §7
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_nan_inf_propagation" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.NaN/Inf propagation §6+§7")

    Let nan be APD.arbitrary_decimal_make_qnan(34, 0)
    Let pos_inf be APD.arbitrary_decimal_make_infinity(0, 34, 0)
    Let neg_inf be APD.arbitrary_decimal_make_infinity(1, 34, 0)
    Let one be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_integer(1, 34)
    Let zero be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_integer(0, 34)

    Note: NaN + 1 = NaN.
    Let r1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(nan, one, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "NaN + 1 is NaN", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_nan(r1), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r1)

    Note: NaN != NaN.
    T.assert_equal(results, "NaN != NaN", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(nan, nan), 0)

    Note: +Inf + 1 = +Inf.
    Let r2 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(pos_inf, one, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "+Inf + 1 = +Inf", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_infinite(r2), 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "+Inf + 1 is positive", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_negative(r2), 0)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r2)

    Note: +Inf + -Inf = NaN.
    Let r3 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(pos_inf, neg_inf, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "+Inf + -Inf = NaN (invalid)", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_nan(r3), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r3)

    Note: +Inf * 0 = NaN.
    Let r4 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_mul(pos_inf, zero, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "+Inf * 0 = NaN (invalid)", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_nan(r4), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r4)

    Note: 1 / 0 = +Inf.
    Let r5 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_div(one, zero, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1 / 0 = +Inf", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_infinite(r5), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r5)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(nan)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(pos_inf)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(neg_inf)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(one)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(zero)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: Negation / abs identity per §5.5.1
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_neg_abs_identities" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.neg/abs identities §5.5.1")

    Let x be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("123.456", 34)
    Let neg_x be APD.arbitrary_decimal_neg(x)
    Let neg_neg_x be APD.arbitrary_decimal_neg(neg_x)
    T.assert_equal(results, "neg(neg(x)) = x", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(x, neg_neg_x), 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "neg(x) is negative", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_negative(neg_x), 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "neg(neg(x)) is not negative", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_negative(neg_neg_x), 0)

    Let abs_x be APD.arbitrary_decimal_abs(x)
    Let abs_neg_x be APD.arbitrary_decimal_abs(neg_x)
    T.assert_equal(results, "abs(x) == abs(neg(x))", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(abs_x, abs_neg_x), 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "abs(x) is not negative", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_negative(abs_x), 0)
    T.assert_equal(results, "abs(neg(x)) is not negative", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_negative(abs_neg_x), 0)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(x)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(neg_x)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(neg_neg_x)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(abs_x)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(abs_neg_x)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: Standard arithmetic vectors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_standard_arithmetic" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.arithmetic vectors")

    Let a1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("3.14", 34)
    Let b1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("2.86", 34)
    Let e1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("6.00", 34)
    Let r1 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_add(a1, b1, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "3.14 + 2.86 = 6.00", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r1, e1), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r1)

    Let a2 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1.5", 34)
    Let b2 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("2.0", 34)
    Let e2 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("3.0", 34)
    Let r2 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_mul(a2, b2, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "1.5 * 2.0 = 3.0", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r2, e2), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a2)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b2)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e2)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r2)

    Let a3 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("100", 34)
    Let b3 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("4", 34)
    Let e3 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("25", 34)
    Let r3 be APD.arbitrary_decimal_div(a3, b3, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "100 / 4 = 25", APD.arbitrary_decimal_eq(r3, e3), 1)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(a3)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(b3)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(e3)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(r3)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: Rounding-mode setter
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_rounding_mode_setter" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.rounding mode setter")

    Let v be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_string("1", 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "default mode is HALF_EVEN", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_rounding_mode(v), 0)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_set_rounding_mode(v, 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "set to HALF_UP", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_rounding_mode(v), 1)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_set_rounding_mode(v, 2)
    T.assert_equal(results, "set to TOWARD_ZERO", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_rounding_mode(v), 2)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_set_rounding_mode(v, 5)
    T.assert_equal(results, "set to HALF_DOWN", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_rounding_mode(v), 5)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_set_rounding_mode(v, 6)
    T.assert_equal(results, "set to HALF_AWAY_FROM_ZERO", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_rounding_mode(v), 6)

    Note: Invalid mode coerces to HALF_EVEN.
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_set_rounding_mode(v, 99)
    T.assert_equal(results, "invalid mode coerces to HALF_EVEN", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_rounding_mode(v), 0)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(v)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: KAT: from_integer / from_decimal128 / from_decimal64 conversions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "test_construction_paths" that takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    T.begin_suite(results, "apd.construction paths")

    Let v_int be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_integer(42, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "from_integer(42) is finite", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_finite(v_int), 1)
    T.assert_equal(results, "from_integer(42) sign is 0", APD.arbitrary_decimal_get_sign(v_int), 0)

    Let v_neg_int be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_integer(-42, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "from_integer(-42) is negative", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_negative(v_neg_int), 1)

    Let v_zero be APD.arbitrary_decimal_from_integer(0, 34)
    T.assert_equal(results, "from_integer(0) is zero", APD.arbitrary_decimal_is_zero(v_zero), 1)

    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(v_int)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(v_neg_int)
    APD.arbitrary_decimal_destroy(v_zero)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be T.create_test_results()

    test_zero_point_one_plus_zero_point_two_multi_precision(results)
    test_one_seventh_repeats_142857(results)
    test_one_third_all_threes(results)
    test_twenty_two_sevenths_approximation(results)
    test_sovereign_grade_preservation(results)
    test_cumulative_sum_50_digit(results)
    test_nan_inf_propagation(results)
    test_neg_abs_identities(results)
    test_standard_arithmetic(results)
    test_rounding_mode_setter(results)
    test_construction_paths(results)

    T.print_summary(results)
    Let exit_code be T.get_failed(results)
    T.destroy_test_results(results)
    Return exit_code
End Process
